# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1820 Missouri lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on August 28, 1820, in order to elect the first lieutenant governor of Missouri upon Missouri acquiring statehood on August 10, 1821.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican nominee William H.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Ashley won the election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The exact results of the election are unknown.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, August 28, 1820, Democratic-Republican nominee William H.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Ashley won the election as he ran unopposed, thereby gaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of lieutenant governor.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Ashley was sworn in as the 1st lieutenant governor of Missouri on September 18, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The **1820–21 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between July 3, 1820, and August 10, 1821.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 17th United States Congress convened on December 3, 1821.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] They coincided with President James Monroe winning reelection unopposed.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] In March 1820, seven House seats transferred from Massachusetts to Maine after the latter seceded from the former to become a separate state.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The size of the House then increased to 187 seats after Missouri achieved statehood in 1821.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The virtually nonpartisan Era of Good Feelings, a period of national political dominance by the Democratic-Republican Party, continued.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Despite small gains, the Federalist Party remained relegated to limited state and local influence.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] There were special elections in 1820 and 1821 to the 16th United States Congress and 17th United States Congress.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Special elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Alabama elected its member August 5–6, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Connecticut elected its members April 2, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Delaware elected its members October 3, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Georgia elected its members October 2, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Illinois elected its member August 7, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Indiana elected its member August 7, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Kentucky elected its members August 7, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Louisiana elected its member July 3–5, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] This was the first election in Maine since its separation from Massachusetts.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] In the previous election, Massachusetts had had 20 representatives.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Seven seats (representing the 14th-20th districts) were reassigned from Massachusetts to Maine.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] In addition, under the terms of the law which admitted Maine to the union, any vacancies in the 16th Congress by Representatives elected to represent Massachusetts but residing in the new states of Maine would be filled by a resident of Maine.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] John Holmes, who had been elected to the House for the former 14th district of Massachusetts was elected as one of the first two senators for Maine.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The vacancy was filled in a special election by Joseph Dane (Federalist).
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Dane was the only Representative officially considered as representing Maine in the 16th Congress.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The Representatives from the 15th-20th districts were still classified as being from Massachusetts for the remainder of the 16th Congress.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Maine elected its members on November 7, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] State law required a majority to win an election, necessitating additional ballots if a majority was not received.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] And, in fact, additional ballots were held on January 22, 1821, and September 10, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Maryland elected its members October 2, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] This was the first election in Massachusetts after the separation of the former District of Maine as the new State of Maine, taking the old 14th – 20th districts with it.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Massachusetts elected its members November 6, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Massachusetts had a majority requirement for election, which was not met in the 2nd district necessitating two additional elections on January 8, 1821, and April 16, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] District numbers differed between source used and elsewhere on Wikipedia; district numbers used elsewhere on Wikipedia used here.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Mississippi elected its member August 7–8, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Missouri was admitted to the union on August 10, 1821, but elections had been held August 28, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] New Hampshire elected its members August 18, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] New Jersey elected its members November 7, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] There were an unusually large number of candidates, 119 candidates according to one contemporary newspaper.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Some candidates ran under an "Anti-Caucus" ticket.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Only 1 of the 6 six incumbents would serve in the next term, as 4 retired and 1 died after re-election.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] New York elected its members April 24–26, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The 21st district, previously a plural district with two seats, was divided into two single-member districts for the 17th Congress, the 21st and 22nd.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The Democratic-Republican party in New York was divided between "Bucktails" and "Clintonians".
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The Clintonians ran on a joint ticket with the remaining Federalists.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] In a few cases, marked as "Clintonian/Federalist" below, it is unclear whether a candidate on the joint ticket was Democratic-Republican or Federalist.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Only five of the twenty-seven incumbents were re-elected to the next term.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Sixteen incumbents retired and five lost re-election.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Despite this high turnover of membership, there was only a one-seat net gain for the Federalists.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] North Carolina elected its members August 9, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Ohio elected its members October 10, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Pennsylvania elected its members October 10, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Rhode Island elected its members August 29, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] South Carolina elected its members October 9–10, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Tennessee elected its members August 9–10, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] In 1820, Vermont returned to using districts.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] This would be the only election in which the 6th district would be used.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Vermont elected its members September 5, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] A majority was required for election, which was not met in the 2nd or 3rd district, requiring additional ballots to achieve a majority.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] The 3rd district required two additional ballots.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] The additional ballots were held December 11, 1820, and February 19, May 1, July 2, September 4, and October 22, 1821.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Virginia elected its members in April 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] There were four territories that had the right to send a delegate to at least part of the 17th Congress, only three of which actually sent delegates.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Missouri Territory's seat remained vacant, as the territory was admitted as the State of Missouri early in the 17th Congress.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] The **1820 United States presidential election in Missouri** took place between November 1 to December 6, 1820.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] The Missouri state legislature chose 3 electors, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] Missouri Territory was formed just after Louisiana was admitted to fill the old space of the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] In 1820, they split off a portion of Missouri Territory into what would become the new state of Missouri.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] However, the heated debate had begun after Congress could not decide whether its electoral votes in the upcoming election would count, or if it should be rejected and would vote in 1824.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] This debate would later be overshadowed with issues regarding the expansion of slavery out west, and whether Missouri would be a free or slave state.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] Eventually, the Missouri Compromise allowed Missouri to be a slave state, however, they could not admit any more states above a line marked by the new Arkansaw Territory.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] On March 6, 1820, Congress passed a law directing Missouri to hold a convention to form a constitution and a state government.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] This law stated that "...the said state, when formed, shall be admitted into the Union, upon an equal footing with the original states, in all respects whatsoever." However, when Congress reconvened in November 1820, the admission of Missouri became an issue of contention.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] Proponents claimed that Missouri had fulfilled the conditions of the law and therefore it was a state; detractors contended that certain provisions of the Missouri Constitution violated the United States Constitution.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] By the time Congress was due to meet to count the electoral votes from the election, this dispute had lasted over two months.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] The counting raised a ticklish problem: if Congress counted Missouri's votes, that would count as recognition that Missouri was a state; on the other hand, if Congress failed to count Missouri's vote, that would count as recognition that Missouri was not a state.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] Instead, the president of the Senate would announce the final tally twice, once with Missouri included and once with it excluded.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] The next day this resolution was introduced in the full House.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] Nonetheless, during the counting of the electoral votes on February 14, 1821, an objection was raised to the votes from Missouri by Representative Arthur Livermore of New Hampshire.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] He argued that since Missouri had not yet officially become a state that Missouri had no right to cast any electoral votes.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] Immediately, Representative John Floyd of Virginia argued that Missouri's votes must be counted.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] Chaos ensued, and order was only restored with the counting of the vote as per the resolution and then adjournment for the day.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-missouri] During this election, Missouri cast their votes for incumbent president James Monroe, and incumbent vice president Daniel D.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] The **1820–21 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, corresponding with James Monroe's landslide re-election.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1820 and 1821, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 1.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] The Democratic-Republican Party gain one-to-five seats (in the general and special elections), assuming almost complete control of the Senate.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] Composition after the June 13 and 14, 1820 elections in Maine.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] In these special elections, the winner was elected during 1820 or before March 4, 1821; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] In these general elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1821; ordered by state.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] All of the elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] In this special election, the winner was elected in 1821 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] John Holmes (Democratic-Republican) was elected as one of the new state's first pair of senators, whose terms began with June 13, 1820 statehood.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] He was elected to the class 1 seat's short term, which ended March 3, 1821, and was re-elected on January 31, 1821, to the term starting March 4, 1821.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] John Chandler (Democratic-Republican) was elected to the class 2 seat's long term, and his term would end on March 3, 1823.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1821-united-states-senate-elections-in-missouri] William Pinkney won election by an unknown number of votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The **1822–23 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between July 1, 1822, and August 14, 1823.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 18th United States Congress convened on December 1, 1823.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] They occurred during President James Monroe's second term.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Following the congressional reapportionment based on the 1820 United States census, the House increased by 26 seats to a total of 213.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Most relative population growth was in the West.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] This was the last House election during the virtually nonpartisan Era of Good Feelings and the largest midterm gain of seats by a President's party.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The Democratic-Republican Party remained nationally dominant, and the Federalist Party was limited to state and local influence.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] This election heralded key change not apparent until the end of the 18th Congress.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The four-way 1824 presidential election, in which all candidates ran as Democratic-Republicans, would result in no candidate winning an Electoral College majority.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Representatives elected to the 18th Congress are often classified by how they voted in the 1825 contingent election, which after a controversial, unanticipated political deal chose John Quincy Adams President, triggering a new, rancorous, abruptly realigned period of partisanship.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] This election marked the second time in American history where the incumbent president's party gained House seats in a midterm election while still losing seats in the Senate, this happened before in 1814 and again in 1902.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Following the 1820 census, 26 new seats were apportioned, with 4 States losing 1 seat each, 9 States gaining between 1 and 8 seats, and the remaining 11 States having no change in apportionment.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] There were special elections in 1822 and 1823 to the 17th United States Congress and 18th United States Congress.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Alabama increased from one to three seats in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The state then changed from a single at-large district to three geographic districts.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Alabama elected its members August 3, 1823, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Connecticut lost one seat in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Connecticut elected its members April 7, 1823, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Delaware was reduced once more from two back to one seat after the fourth census, which number has remained constant to the present day.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] At the time of the October 1, 1822, election, the second seat in Delaware's at-large district was vacant, so there was only one incumbent going into the election.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Georgia gained one seat in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Georgia elected its members October 7, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Illinois elected its sole at-large member August 5, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Indiana gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census, and elected its members August 5, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Indiana's single at-large seat in the 17th Congress was empty at the time of the election, previous incumbent William Hendricks (Democratic-Republican) having resigned to run for Governor of Indiana.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Jonathan Jennings (Jackson D-R), elected to the new 2nd district, was elected in the ensuing special election to fill the at-large district for the remainder of the 17th Congress.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Kentucky gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Kentucky elected its members August 5, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Louisiana gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Louisiana elected its members July 1–3, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Although Maine neither gained nor lost seats after the 1820 United States census, redistricting placed two incumbents into the 3rd district.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Maine elected its members April 7, 1823, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Maine law required a majority for election, with additional ballots taken if a majority were not achieved.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] This proved necessary in 1822 in the 1st, 3rd, 4th, and 6th districts, but all members were still chosen before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Maryland elected its members October 7, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Massachusetts elected its members November 4, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Massachusetts law required a majority for election, which was not met in 3 districts, necessitating additional elections on March 3, 1823, and May 12, 1823; nevertheless, all elections were complete before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Mississippi elected its member August 5–6, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Missouri elected its member October 7, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] New Hampshire elected its members August 26, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] New Hampshire law required a candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters for election, that is 1/12 of votes.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] Only five candidates received the requisite majority, and so a May 11, 1823, run-off election was held for the sixth seat.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] New Jersey elected its members October 15, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] New York's representation increased after the 1820 United States census from 27 to 34 seats, elected from 30 districts, two with two members each, and one with three members.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] New York elected its members November 4–6, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] As in the previous election, the Democratic-Republican Party in New York was divided into two factions, the "Bucktails" and the Clintonians, which distinction is not marked here.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p01] The Clintonians and the Federalists ran on a joint ticket in 1822 as in 1821, in some cases, it's unclear which party a candidate belonged to, those are marked Crawford Federalist.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] North Carolina's delegation remained unchanged after the census, at thirteen seats.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] North Carolina elected its members August 14, 1823, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Ohio gained eight seats in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Ohio elected its members October 8, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Pennsylvania gained three seats in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Pennsylvania elected its members October 8, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Rhode Island elected its members August 27, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] South Carolina elected its members February 12–13, 1823.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Tennessee gained three seats in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Tennessee elected its members August 7–8, 1823, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Vermont lost one seat in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] For the 1822 election, Vermont switched back to using a single at-large district.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] This would be the last year that Vermont would use an at-large district until 1932, when its representation was reduced to a single seat.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Vermont elected its members September 3, 1822.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Virginia lost one seat in reapportionment following the 1820 United States census.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Nineteen incumbents ran for re-election leaving three open seats.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] Virginia elected its members in April 1823, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1822-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-missouri-p02] There were three territories with the right to send delegates to the 18th Congress.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1824-missouri-gubernatorial-election] The **1824 Missouri gubernatorial election** was held on August 2, 1824, Frederick Bates defeated Lt.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1824-missouri-gubernatorial-election] Both candidates were members of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1824-missouri-gubernatorial-election] The death of Frederick Bates in August 1825, meant that the next election for governor of Missouri would be held little more than a year after this election.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1824-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1824 Missouri lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on August 2, 1824, in order to elect the lieutenant governor of Missouri.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1824-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican nominee Benjamin Harrison Reeves won the election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1824-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, August 2, 1824, Democratic-Republican nominee Benjamin Harrison Reeves won the election as he ran unopposed, thereby retaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of lieutenant governor.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1824-missouri-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Reeves was sworn in as the 2nd lieutenant governor of Missouri on November 15, 1824.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 Missouri gubernatorial election** was held on August 4, 1828.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election] Governor John Miller was elected unopposed to a full term as governor (having previously won the 1825 special election to succeed Abraham J.
[src:1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election/1828-missouri-gubernatorial-election] Williams, who succeeded the late Frederick Bates).
